'''Kari Voutilainen''' (born in 1962) is a Finnish watchmaker residing in [[Môtiers]], [[Switzerland]]. He started an independent watchmaking business in 2002, building a limited number of handmade [[timekeeper]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Artisan d'Horlogerie d'Art Voutilainen|url=http://www.voutilainen.ch/|accessdate=2010-08-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Interview of Kari Voutilainen (in French)|url=http://www.horlogerie-suisse.com/horlomag/articles-horlogers/00154/interview-de-kari-voutilainen|accessdate=2010-08-16}}</ref> In 2005, he introduced the world's first decimal repeater sounding hours, ten-minute intervals and then minutes.<ref name="iw_may2006">{{Citation|first=Curtis D.|last=Thomson|issue=May, 2006|title=Decimal Points|journal=International Watch|pages=137–140|url=http://tempered-online.com/voutilainen/articles/KariVLRPDF.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref> Voutilainen is Member of the [[Académie Horlogère des Créateurs Indépendants|AHCI]] and created together with [[Andreas Strehler]] the watch "Chapter III" for [[Maitres du Temps|Maîtres du Temps]] in 2012.<ref>Watch Worldwide Magazine, Thailand, Volume 08, No95, February 2013, Page 70-73</ref>
