The '''American Progressive Bag Alliance''' (APBA) represents the U.S. plastic bag manufacturing and recycling industry, which employs nearly 25,000 workers in 40 states. Founded in 2005, the APBA proactively promotes product lines and leads numerous public policy initiatives that serve as the frontline defense against plastic bag bans and taxes nationwide.
With the support of the industry’s workers, the APBA promotes American-made plastic products that are the smartest, most environmentally-friendly choice at the checkout counter for both retailers and consumers.
==Activities== Plastic retail bags – the kind you get from your grocer or at the corner store — are being targeted for bans and taxes in communities around the country. Bans and taxes have a negative impact on working families and seniors on fixed incomes, but they don’t help the environment in any meaningful way.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bagtheban.com/learn-the-facts/environment/|title=Plastic Bags and the Environment|last=|first=|date=|website=Bag the Ban|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> With the support of the industry’s workers, the APBA works throughout the country to promote American-made plastic products that are the smartest, most environmentally-friendly<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www2.mst.dk/Udgiv/publications/2018/02/978-87-93614-73-4.pdf|title=Life cycle assessment of grocery carrier bags|last=|first=|date=February 2018|website=Ministry of Environment and Food of Denmark|publisher=The Danish Environmental Protection Agency|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> choice at the checkout counter for both retailers and consumers.
